        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                You are given an array of n strings strs, all of the same length. The strings can be arranged such that
                there is one on each line, making a grid. You want to delete the columns that are not sorted
                lexicographically.
                Return the number of columns that you will delete. A column is considered sorted if for every row index
                i
                where 1 <= i < n, strs[i-1][col] <=strs[i][col]. </p>
                    <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                        Input: strs = ["cba","daf","ghi"] → Output: 1. The grid is: c b a, d a f, g h i. Columns 0 and 2
                        are sorted,
                        but column 1 is not (b > a), so we delete 1 column.
                        Input: strs = ["a","b"] → Output: 0. The grid is: a, b. Column 0 is sorted, so no deletions
                        needed.
                        Input: strs = ["zyx","wvu","tsr"] → Output: 3. All columns are unsorted (decreasing order), so
                        delete all 3.
                    </p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    int minDeletionSize(vector&lt;string&gt;&amp; strs) {
        int n = strs.size();
        int m = strs[0].size();
        int del = 0;
        // Traverse column-wise
        for (int c = 0; c &lt; m; c++) {
            for (int r = 1; r &lt; n; r++) {
                // If sorting condition fails
                if (strs[r][c] &lt; strs[r - 1][c]) {
                    del++;
                    break; // no need to check further rows
                }
            }
        }
        return del;
    }
};</code></pre>
